ce:section.ce:para:
The degradation rates of MB with different catalysts under visible light irradiation at different times are shown in Fig. 4
                     . The inset in Fig. 4 shows the color contrast of the aqueous solution before and after light irradiation. MB was almost completely degraded after 4h of light irradiation. As the growth of the time, the absorption peak will decline gradually at 664nm. This finding is interesting because the photocatalytic degradation rates of GQDs, GQDs-PEIs, and GQDs-PEGs decreased successively. The degradation of organic dyes by using TiO2, Bi2WO6, and CaIn2O4 as catalysts is described as an adsorption-oxidation-desorption mechanism [27–29]. GQDs could reduce MB compared with TiO2 reported by Zhuo et al. [3] Free radical species, such as •OH and ••O−2, are possibly responsible for the degradation of MB, and radicals have been detected in electron spin resonance (ESR) spectra during visible light irradiation (Fig. 5
                     ). ESR spin-trip technique (with DMPO) was employed to probe the nature of the reactive oxygen species generated during the visible light irradiation [30]. Under experimental conditions, no ESR signals of •OH and ••O−2 radicals were observed in the dark. There were obvious characteristic quartet peaks of the DMPO–•OH adduct and DMPO–••O−2 adduct in the presence of the GQDs after being illuminated with visible light in MB solution.
